ith timestamps\\n\\nThe Telegram group session ended around 10:56 UTC, and the heartbeat cron finished its cycle, which triggered a new instance at 11:00 UTC. There's also a delivery retry cron stuck since around 10:04 UTC that's been retried. I need to verify the Telegram session status since it's showing as ended in the logs.\\n\\nLooking at the timestamps more carefully, the Telegram session ended at 10:56 UTC while the 5p report from the other cron came in at 10:59 UTC, so that report was from a different session. The current cron instance was spawned at 11:00 UTC and is now running.\\n\\nComparing the session states: the Telegram group session ended between 10:56 and 11:01 UTC, the QLHV group session also ended at 10:49 UTC, and the cron instance from 6f3323ef was replaced by the new ed2d0b5d instance at 11:00 UTC. I see that the previous heartbeat report was actually sent from this exact same cron session, so the state comparison is about detecting whether anything has changed since the last report at 10:50 UTC. Looking at what's actually shifted: the QLHV group session ended, and there's a new stuck cron for Telegram delivery that's been retrying for about an hour. I'm looking at the active sessions count now—the DTLX group session, QLHV direct session, and DTLX BE API session are all done, so I need to recount what's actually running. The cron session itself is the current one executing, and I should verify if any of the child sessions from the previous cron runs are still active or if they've all finished. I'm seeing a list of completed sessions, some of which show an endedAt timestamp. I'm seeing that both child sessions from the 5p cron ended around the same time as the Telegram delivery retry cron, so I need to figure out what the actual state was versus what the heartbeat-state.json file recorded. Looking at the discrepancies, the 5p report cron was reSpawned and the QLHV Ecosystem Group session was running, but the heartbeat didn't capture the delivery