new stuck cron is now stuck for longer than it was before, and the DTLX group session is also gone. The 5p cron appears to still be running with new activity. Let me verify the Telegram session status to confirm this is actually a change from the previous report. Looking at the Telegram session's metadata more carefully - it's marked as \"ended\" with an `endedAt` timestamp of 1776163783190, which converts to approximately 10:43 UTC, so it did finish at some point.\n\nWait, I need to double-check the math here. That timestamp in milliseconds actually corresponds to around 14:56 UTC, not 10:43 - so the session is still running. Let me verify this calculation against the other timestamps to make sure I'm reading the session state correctly. The math checks out—10:43 UTC is correct, not 14:43, so the Telegram session actually ended before the 5p report was sent from a different cron instance. Now I can identify what changed between the 10:50 UTC snapshot and the current 11:01 UTC state.\n\nThe Telegram session for the QLHV Ecosystem Group has ended, the Telegram delivery retry cron is still stuck and retrying with an updated message, and the main session that was running at 10:50 has now finished. I'm also counting through the active sessions to get a clearer picture of what's currently running versus what I've already documented. I'm finishing the count of active sessions and noting there's a new cron for Telegram delivery retry that's been stuck for about an hour, which adds a blocker. The Telegram group session ended while the new 5p cron spawned, so the active sessions stayed at 2 total. I'm trying to reconcile the timeline—the last heartbeat was at 10:50, but the previous report was sent at 10:59, so I need to clarify when that report actually went out.\n\nLooking back at the actual session states, I can see the Telegram group session ended at 10:43, which contradicts the heartbeat state showing it as still running at 10:50. The cron session has been running the whole time, the DTLX 5p session ended around 10:39, the main session ended at 10:41, and the DTLX group session ended at 10:55—so there's a discrepancy between what the heartbeat reported and what actually happened.\n\nComparing to the current time of 11:01 UTC, the DTLX group session has now ended as well, and the cron for Telegram delivery retry is still stuck and retrying. The QLHV direct session and main session remain ended, and the DTLX BE API session is still done.\n\nLooking at the complete session list, the QLHV Ecosystem group session has also ended by 11:01 UTC. The main session (heartbeat) ended at 10:41, and the DTLX BE API session is marked as done but without an explicit end timestamp listed.\n\nSo the active sessions are the 5p cron (current), the Telegram delivery retry cron (stuck and running), and the QLHV Ecosystem group session (running). I need to report the key changes: the QLHV Ecosystem group session ended, and the Telegram delivery retry cron is still stuck and retrying. The blockers remain the same—the Telegram gateway timeout and the DTLX subagent failures with model errors. The 5p cron is still running. Looking at the blockers section, there's a discrepancy between what the state file recorded and what was actually reported to the user—the state mentioned a timeout issue since around 10:00 UTC, but the report specifically flagged the Telegram delivery retry cron as the stuck component. I should clarify what was actually communicated versus what was in the persistent state.\n\nNow comparing the current state against the last known snapshot, I can see the Telegram group session has ended since 10:50 UTC, and the Telegram delivery retry cron remains stuck and actively retrying. I'm now looking at what active sessions are currently running.\n\nThe MCP connections are all healthy, and the scheduled cron jobs are functioning as expected. So the pipeline status hasn't changed—it's still degraded due to the pre-existing Telegram delivery blocker,