9.9 million ms (2h45m), then the session would have started around 08:05 UTC. But endedAt shows 10:39 UTC, which is earlier than updatedAt—that doesn't add up unless endedAt is actually from a child session rather than the parent cron itself. The child sessions listed are various agents that ran as part of the cron, each with their own timestamps and completion status.\n\nLooking at the child session details, one of them ended around 10:39 UTC, which might be what's showing up as the endedAt value. This could mean the cron itself is still running while some of its child processes have completed.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that the cron process spawned child agents that ran for about 9.9 million milliseconds total, and one of those ended at 10:39 UTC, which is why that timestamp appears as the endedAt value. So the cron is still active and processing work, even though some of its child sessions have finished. endedAt = 10:39 UTC = the time when one of the child agents completed, not when the cron itself ended.\n\nActually, I think the `endedAt` of 1776163783190 corresponds to when the LAST child agent (or a specific child) ended, and the cron itself is still running. The `runtimeMs` of 9.9M ms = 2.75h is the cumulative time of child agents.\n\nOR the `endedAt` is when the cron STARTED executing (not ended), and the field name is misleading.\n\nOR the cron started at 08:05 UTC (from runtimeMs) and the `endedAt` is when it last sent a heartbeat.\n\nI'm going in circles. Let me just look at the facts:\n\n1. The DTLX cron session shows `status: \"running\"` — it's currently active\n2. The `updatedAt` is 10:44 UTC — it's been updated recently\n3. `startedAt` = 08:05 UTC — started ~3 hours ago\n4. `endedAt` = 10:39 UTC — possibly when the last child agent ended, or possibly a data artifact\n\nComparing this to the previous heartbeat from 10:50 UTC, the cron was already running then with a `lastSeen` of 10:50 UTC. Now at 11:05 UTC it's still running with an `updatedAt` of 10:44 UTC, so the session is stable and the cron is the same one that's been executing all along.\n\nSince the heartbeat state file hasn't been updated since 10:50 UTC, I need to write the current state. The cron (ed2d0b5d) is still running as of 11:05 UTC. The other session that was running at 10:50 UTC (the one with ID 6f3323ef) has ended.\n\nLooking at the DTLX cron, it ended around 10:39 UTC based on the session data, which is before the 10:50 UTC heartbeat. The heartbeat state file shows it as still running at 10:50 UTC, but that's a stale state—it likely ended shortly after or the heartbeat was captured just before it finished. The state file shows 6f3323ef as running at 10:50 UTC, but the session data indicates it ended at 10:39 UTC—so the heartbeat captured stale state before the cron actually finished. The key insight is that both the previous report at 10:59 UTC and this one at 11:05 UTC are coming from the same cron instance (ed2d0b5d), which started around 08:05 UTC and is still running. Looking at the session list, I can see ed2d0b5d is running while 6f3323ef is ended, which matches the previous heartbeat state. The cron has been active since 08:05 UTC and updated at 11:02 UTC, so it's definitely still running. The heartbeat timestamps need to be recalculated more carefully—10:50 UTC converts to 1776163800000 ms, but I'm getting confused about whether the cron actually started at 08:05 or if there's something else going on with the session timestamps. So the cron started at 08:05 UTC and has been running for about 3 hours. Looking at the session state, it's still actively running with recent updates at 11:02 UTC. The heartbeat file from 10:50 UTC is now outdated—it's been 15 minutes since that snapshot—so I need to write the current state with the new timestamps.\n\nComparing to the previous report at 10:59 UTC, the active sessions haven't changed, the Telegram retry cron is still stuck, and everything else is stable. There's nothing new to report